",["$r","h3",null,{"id":"displaying-different-content-on-the-server-and-the-client","children":"Displaying different content on the server and the client "}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":["If your app uses server rendering (either ",["$r","a",null,{"href":"/reference/react-dom/server","children":"directly"}]," or via a ",["$r","a",null,{"href":"/learn/start-a-new-react-project#production-grade-react-frameworks","children":"framework"}],"), your component will render in two different environments. On the server, it will render to produce the initial HTML. On the client, React will run the rendering code again so that it can attach your event handlers to that HTML. This is why, for ",["$r","a",null,{"href":"/reference/react-dom/client/hydrateRoot#hydrating-server-rendered-html","children":"hydration"}]," to work, your initial render output must be identical on the client and the server."]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":["In rare cases, you might need to display different content on the client. For example, if your app reads some data from ",["$r","a",null,{"href":"https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Window/localStorage","target":"_blank","rel":"nofollow noopener noreferrer","children":["$r","code",null,{"children":"localStorage"}]}],", it can’t possibly do that on the server. Here is how you could implement this:"]}],"
",["$r","pre",null,{"children":["$r","code",null,{"className":"language-js","children":"function MyComponent() {
  const [didMount, setDidMount] = useState(false);

  useEffect(() => {
    setDidMount(true);
  }, []);

  if (didMount) {
    // ... return client-only JSX ...
  }  else {
    // ... return initial JSX ...
  }
}
"}]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":["While the app is loading, the user will see the initial render output. Then, when it’s loaded and hydrated, your Effect will run and set ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"didMount"}]," to ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"true"}],", triggering a re-render. This will switch to the client-only render output. Effects don’t run on the server, so this is why ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"didMount"}]," was ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"false"}]," during the initial server render."]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":"Use this pattern sparingly. Keep in mind that users with a slow connection will see the initial content for quite a bit of time—potentially, many seconds—so you don’t want to make jarring changes to your component’s appearance. In many cases, you can avoid the need for this by conditionally showing different things with CSS."}],"
