",["$r","h3",null,{"id":"my-effect-runs-after-every-re-render","children":"My Effect runs after every re-render "}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":"First, check that you haven’t forgotten to specify the dependency array:"}],"
",["$r","pre",null,{"children":["$r","code",null,{"className":"language-js","meta":"{3}","children":"useEffect(() => {
  // ...
}); // 🚩 No dependency array: re-runs after every render!
"}]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":"If you’ve specified the dependency array but your Effect still re-runs in a loop, it’s because one of your dependencies is different on every re-render."}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":"You can debug this problem by manually logging your dependencies to the console:"}],"
",["$r","pre",null,{"children":["$r","code",null,{"className":"language-js","meta":"{5}","children":"  useEffect(() => {
    // ..
  }, [serverUrl, roomId]);

  console.log([serverUrl, roomId]);
"}]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":["You can then right-click on the arrays from different re-renders in the console and select “Store as a global variable” for both of them. Assuming the first one got saved as ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"temp1"}]," and the second one got saved as ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"temp2"}],", you can then use the browser console to check whether each dependency in both arrays is the same:"]}],"
",["$r","pre",null,{"children":["$r","code",null,{"className":"language-js","children":"Object.is(temp1[0], temp2[0]); // Is the first dependency the same between the arrays?
Object.is(temp1[1], temp2[1]); // Is the second dependency the same between the arrays?
Object.is(temp1[2], temp2[2]); // ... and so on for every dependency ...
"}]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":"When you find the dependency that is different on every re-render, you can usually fix it in one of these ways:"}],"
